<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[147,1244,1300,1578]" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[147,249,1301,1322]" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">Remarks.</emphasis>
Additional material from Pant-y-ffynnon, comprising two isolated non-ungual phalanges (field numbers P65/30 and P65/49), an isolated metapodial (field number P65/23) and an isolated ungual (field number P65/45), were considered to possibly be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[882,994,1365,1386]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[882,994,1365,1386]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Warrener [
<bibRefCitation author="Warrener D." box="[1159,1186,1364,1386]" journalOrPublisher="University College London (University of London)" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" refId="ref19918" refString="41. Warrener D. 1983 An archosaurian fauna from a Welsh locality. University College London (University of London)." title="An archosaurian fauna from a Welsh locality" type="book" year="1983">41</bibRefCitation>
] and interpretative drawings of these elements were provided therein. These elements cannot be confidently attributed to any other known taxa known from Pant-y-ffynnon and were likely recovered from the same block as the partial left ischium of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[584,693,1461,1482]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[584,693,1461,1482]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(field number P65/66b) as indicated by the shared number 65 in their field number. The location of these elements is currently unknown and there is no record of them in the NHMUK collections. Since these elements do not exhibit diagnostic theropod features, there is currently insufficient support for an unequivocal attribution of this material to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[1131,1238,1556,1578]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[1131,1238,1556,1578]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[147,1245,1599,1941]" lastBlockId="6.[148,1245,1693,1747]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[147,413,1599,1621]" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">Ontogenetic assessment.</emphasis>
The limited material currently referable to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[878,987,1599,1621]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[878,987,1599,1621]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
limits interpretations of intraspecific variation related to ontogeny, and, therefore, a comprehensive assessment of maturity cannot be provided. However, we approximate the ontogenetic stage of the holotype NHMUK PV R 37591 by scoring it for the maturity assessment matrix that has been formulated for early theropods (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fischer" baseAuthorityYear="1883" box="[1133,1244,1695,1716]" class="Reptilia" family="Coelophysidae" genus="Coelophysis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Coelophysis</taxonomicName>
bauri
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[251,400,1727,1749]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">M. rhodesiensis</emphasis>
) and a non-dinosaurian dinosauriform (
<emphasis box="[822,1009,1727,1748]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName box="[822,931,1727,1748]" class="Reptilia" family="Silesauridae" genus="Asilisaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thecodontia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Asilisaurus</taxonomicName>
kongwe
</emphasis>
) [
<bibRefCitation author="Griffin C." box="[1029,1054,1727,1749]" journalOrPublisher="J. Anat." pageId="3" pageNumber="15" pagination="604 - 640" part="232" refId="ref20419" refString="54. Griffin C. 2018 Developmental patterns and variation among early theropods. J. Anat. 232, 604 - 640. (doi: 10.1111 / joa. 12775)" title="Developmental patterns and variation among early theropods" type="journal article" year="2018">54</bibRefCitation>
– 
<bibRefCitation author="Griffin CT &amp; Nesbitt SJ" box="[1066,1094,1726,1748]" journalOrPublisher="Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" pagination="14 757 - 14 762" part="113" refId="ref20507" refString="56. Griffin CT, Nesbitt SJ. 2016 Anomalously high variation in postnatal development is ancestral for dinosaurs but lost in birds. Proc. Natl Acad. Sci. USA 113, 14 757 - 14 762. (doi: 10.1073 / pnas. 1613813113)" title="Anomalously high variation in postnatal development is ancestral for dinosaurs but lost in birds" type="journal article" year="2016">56</bibRefCitation>
]. Based on the results of our phylogenetic analysis (see below), these taxa provide a narrow phylogenetic bracket for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="3" pageNumber="15" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="15">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the characters are, therefore, likely suitable for approximating the maturity of this new taxon (see also [
<bibRefCitation author="Griffin CT &amp; Nesbitt SJ" box="[251,279,1822,1845]" journalOrPublisher="Anat. Rec." pageId="3" pageNumber="15" pagination="1158 - 1169" part="303" refId="ref20556" refString="57. Griffin CT, Nesbitt SJ. 2020 Does the maximum body size of theropods increase across the Triassic - Jurassic boundary? Integrating ontogeny, phylogeny, and body size. Anat. Rec. 303, 1158 - 1169. (doi: 10.1002 / ar. 24130)" title="Does the maximum body size of theropods increase across the Triassic - Jurassic boundary? Integrating ontogeny, phylogeny, and body size" type="journal article" year="2020">57</bibRefCitation>
]). However, it is important to consider that it cannot be confidently ascertained whether all characters that were scored are truly ontogenetically dependent for this specific taxon. Out of 32 characters of the maturity assessment matrix, 16 could be scored for NHMUK PV R 37591. Eight characters were scored as mature (1) and another eight were scored as immature (0). None of the characters considered highly informative of maturity (see fig. 22 
<emphasis box="[805,815,1778,1799]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="16">a</emphasis>
in [
<bibRefCitation author="Griffin C." box="[854,881,1777,1800]" journalOrPublisher="J. Anat." pageId="4" pageNumber="16" pagination="604 - 640" part="232" refId="ref20419" refString="54. Griffin C. 2018 Developmental patterns and variation among early theropods. J. Anat. 232, 604 - 640. (doi: 10.1111 / joa. 12775)" title="Developmental patterns and variation among early theropods" type="journal article" year="2018">54</bibRefCitation>
]) are scored as 1, nor are any of the characters considered highly informative of immaturity scored as 0. Of the sequence order of mature state attainment (between 1 and 29) [54,57], NHMUK PV R 37591 has a relative minimum maturity of 5 based on the presence of a mound-like dorsolateral trochanter on the femur (character 16, state 1 [
<bibRefCitation author="Whiteside DI &amp; Duffin CJ" box="[1133,1158,1873,1895]" journalOrPublisher="Zool. J. Linn. Soc." pageId="4" pageNumber="16" pagination="677 - 705" part="179" refId="ref18718" refString="16. Whiteside DI, Duffin CJ. 2017 Late Triassic terrestrial microvertebrates from Charles Moore ' s ' Microlestes ' quarry, Holwell, Somerset, UK. Zool. J. Linn. Soc. 179, 677 - 705. (doi: 10.1111 / zoj. 12458)" title="Late Triassic terrestrial microvertebrates from Charles Moore ' s ' Microlestes ' quarry, Holwell, Somerset, UK" type="journal article" year="2017">16</bibRefCitation>
– 
<bibRefCitation author="Whiteside DI &amp; Duffin CJ &amp; Gill PG &amp; Marshall JEA &amp; Benton MJ" box="[1170,1181,1873,1896]" journalOrPublisher="Palaeontol. Pol." pageId="4" pageNumber="16" pagination="257 - 287" part="67" refId="ref17991" refString="1. Whiteside DI, Duffin CJ, Gill PG, Marshall JEA, Benton MJ. 2016 The Late Triassic and Early Jurassic fissure faunas from Bristol and South Wales: stratigraphy and setting. Palaeontol. Pol. 67, 257 - 287. (doi: 10.4202 / pp. 2016.67 _ 257)" title="The Late Triassic and Early Jurassic fissure faunas from Bristol and South Wales: stratigraphy and setting" type="journal article" year="2016">1</bibRefCitation>
]), the presence of the 
<emphasis box="[313,600,1905,1926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="16">linea intermuscularis caudalis</emphasis>
on the femur (18–1), and the presence of an ‘obturator ridge’ on the femur (20–1), and a maximum maturity of 19 based on the co-ossification of less than four sacral vertebrae (2–0), the absence of co-ossification between the ilium and pubis (8–0), the absence of an ‘anterolateral scar’ on the femur (19–0), and the presence of a gracile and thin fourth trochanter of the femur (23–0). The relative maximum maturity indicates that the holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[974,1083,1873,1894]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="5" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[974,1083,1873,1894]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="17">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was likely not fully skeletally mature, but the relatively large number of characters scored as 1 indicates that it likely also did not represent an early ontogenetic stage. For example, the holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spiekman &amp; Ezcurra &amp; Butler &amp; Fraser &amp; Maidment" authorityYear="2021" box="[953,1063,1937,1958]" class="Reptilia" family="Herrerasauridae" genus="Pendraig" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Saurischia" pageId="5" pageNumber="17" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="milnerae">
<emphasis box="[953,1063,1937,1958]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="17">P. milnerae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is interpreted as more skeletally mature than the type specimens of 
<emphasis box="[680,913,1693,1714]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="18">Liliensternus liliensterni</emphasis>
and as mature as or potentially more mature than the holotype of 
<emphasis box="[497,677,1725,1747]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="18">Gojirasaurus quayi</emphasis>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Griffin CT &amp; Nesbitt SJ" box="[690,718,1724,1746]" journalOrPublisher="Anat. Rec." pageId="6" pageNumber="18" pagination="1158 - 1169" part="303" refId="ref20556" refString="57. Griffin CT, Nesbitt SJ. 2020 Does the maximum body size of theropods increase across the Triassic - Jurassic boundary? Integrating ontogeny, phylogeny, and body size. Anat. Rec. 303, 1158 - 1169. (doi: 10.1002 / ar. 24130)" title="Does the maximum body size of theropods increase across the Triassic - Jurassic boundary? Integrating ontogeny, phylogeny, and body size" type="journal article" year="2020">57</bibRefCitation>
], which are considerably larger than the new taxon.
</paragraph>
